"{\n    \"Title\": \"December 31, 2012 and 2011Notes to the consolidated financial statements\",\n    \"row 1\": \"(in thousands of dollars)\",\n    \"row 2\": \"5. Financial instruments: fair value and risk management (continued)\",\n    \"row 3\": \"Fair value hierarchy (continued)\",\n    \"row 4\": \"The following was a summary of the fair value classification levels as at December 31, 2011:\",\n    \"row 5\": \"Level 1 Level 2 Level 3 Total\",\n    \"row 6\": \"$ $ $ $\",\n    \"row 7\": \"Financial assets\",\n    \"row 8\": \"Short-term investments - 16,139 - 16,139\",\n    \"row 9\": \"Long-term investments - 1,318 - 1,318\",\n    \"row 10\": \"- 17,457 - 17,457\",\n    \"row 11\": \"Financial liabilities\",\n    \"row 12\": \"Interest rate swap - 2,027 - 2,027\",\n    \"row 13\": \"There were no transfers of investments between Level 1 and Level 2 during 2012 and 2011.\",\n    \"row 14\": \"Financial nsk management\",\n    \"row 15\": \"In the normal course of business, the Port Authority is exposed to a variety of financial risks: price risk,\",\n    \"row 16\": \"interest rate risk, liquidity risk and credit risk. The Port Authority's primary risk management objective is\",\n    \"row 17\": \"to preserve capital. Risk management strategies, as discussed below, are designed and implemented to\",\n    \"row 18\": \"ensure the Port Authority's risks and related exposures are consistent with its objectives and risk\",\n    \"row 19\": \"tolerances.\",\n    \"row 20\": \"Market risk\",\n    \"row 21\": \"Market risk is managed by the Port Authority's investment policy which requires a diversified portfolio of\",\n    \"row 22\": \"allowable investments pursuant to Section 32 of the Canada Marine Act. The Port Authority does not\",\n    \"row 23\": \"have any financial instruments which are subject to significant market risk.\",\n    \"row 24\": \"Credit nsk\",\n    \"row 25\": \"The Port Authority's principal financial assets are cash and cash equivalents, short-term investments,\",\n    \"row 26\": \"accounts receivable and long-term investments, which are subject to credit risk. The carrying amounts of\",\n    \"row 27\": \"financial assets on the statement of financial position, represents the Port Authority's maximum credit\",\n    \"row 28\": \"exposure at the date of the statement of financial position.\",\n    \"row 29\": \"The Port Authority's credit risk is primarily attributable to its accounts receivables. The amounts\",\n    \"row 30\": \"disclosed in the statement of financial position of accounts receivable are net of allowance for doubtful\",\n    \"row 31\": \"accounts, estimated by the management of the Port Authority based on previous experience and its\",\n    \"row 32\": \"assessment of the current economic environment. In order to reduce its risk, management has adopted\",\n    \"row 33\": \"credit policies that include regular review of credit limits.\",\n    \"row 34\": \"The credit risk on cash and cash equivalents and short term investments is limited because the\",\n    \"row 35\": \"counterparties are chartered banks with high credit-ratings assigned by national credit-rating agencies.\",\n    \"row 36\": \"The credit risk of long-term investments is mitigated because the instruments heid are Canadian\",\n    \"row 37\": \"commercial banks, provincial and federal government bonds.\",\n    \"row 38\": \"Page 18\"\n}"